body:
We are observing thousands of unrooted `MethodInfo[]` objects in our prod heap dumps. Example output from `dotnet-dump` `dumpheap -stat -dead`:

```C#
00007f487db5bd78    73966     25371816 System.Reflection.MethodInfo[]
```

We've noticed that these arrays contain methods from the `System.Convert` class. Searching for `typeof(Convert)` in EFCore code-base has a single match: https://github.com/search?q=repo%3Adotnet%2Fefcore%20typeof(Convert)&type=code in [SqlServerConvertTranslator](https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/blob/e2c1e169cb4595d12955465f3b44f63223fb5402/src/EFCore.SqlServer/Query/Internal/SqlServerConvertTranslator.cs#L45).

At first, we ignored this because reflection result is saved in a `static readonly` field. However, after running a profiling session with Rider's memory profiler, we saw `SqlServerConvertTranslator` in many stacktraces: ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4797942/221273348-0d23e416-595f-4b95-bd62-ee2c504a46b9.png)

The problem is that even though the result is stored/cached in a `static` field, it stores an `IEnumerable`, which is evaluated on each `SupportedMethods.Contains(method)` call in `SqlServerConvertTranslator.Translate`.

I don't know the EFCore codebase so maybe part of this behavior is WAI. Maybe this method isn't supposed to be called frequently and some non-standard thing we are doing is causing it to be called more frequently. For example, we use linqkit and have some custom expression builder code to optimize `Contains` queries etc.

However, I thought it is still worth fixing the extra allocation given that the fix is as easy as adding a `ToList`. Here is an example code I wrote to reproduce the issue:

```c#
using System.Reflection;
 
public static class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        const int numIterations = 100000;
        var methodInfo = typeof(Convert).GetTypeInfo().GetDeclaredMethods(nameof(Convert.ToBoolean)).First();
 
        PrintGcInfo();
        
        for (var i = 0; i < numIterations; ++i)
        {
            if (SupportedMethodsEnumerable.Contains(methodInfo))
            {
                // Do nothing.
            }
        }
 
        PrintGcInfo();
    }
 
    private static void PrintGcInfo()
    {
        Console.WriteLine(
            "[{0:hh:mm:ss tt zz}] TotalAllocatedMb={1:0.00}, TotalPauseMs={2:0.00}",
            DateTime.UtcNow,
            GC.GetTotalAllocatedBytes(precise: true) / 1024.0 / 1024.0,
            GC.GetTotalPauseDuration().TotalMilliseconds);
    }
    
    private static readonly Dictionary<string, string> TypeMapping = new()
    {
        [nameof(Convert.ToBoolean)] = "bit",
        [nameof(Convert.ToByte)] = "tinyint",
        [nameof(Convert.ToDecimal)] = "decimal(18, 2)",
        [nameof(Convert.ToDouble)] = "float",
        [nameof(Convert.ToInt16)] = "smallint",
        [nameof(Convert.ToInt32)] = "int",
        [nameof(Convert.ToInt64)] = "bigint",
        [nameof(Convert.ToString)] = "nvarchar(max)"
    };
 
    private static readonly List<Type> SupportedTypes = new()
    {
        typeof(bool),
        typeof(byte),
        typeof(DateTime),
        typeof(decimal),
        typeof(double),
        typeof(float),
        typeof(int),
        typeof(long),
        typeof(short),
        typeof(string)
    };
 
    private static readonly IEnumerable<MethodInfo> SupportedMethodsEnumerable
        = TypeMapping.Keys
            .SelectMany(
                t => typeof(Convert).GetTypeInfo().GetDeclaredMethods(t)
                    .Where(
                        m => m.GetParameters().Length == 1
                             && SupportedTypes.Contains(m.GetParameters().First().ParameterType)));
 
    private static readonly IList<MethodInfo> SupportedMethodsList
        = TypeMapping.Keys
            .SelectMany(
                t => typeof(Convert).GetTypeInfo().GetDeclaredMethods(t)
                    .Where(
                        m => m.GetParameters().Length == 1
                             && SupportedTypes.Contains(m.GetParameters().First().ParameterType)))
            .ToList();
```

This prints the following output on my Linux machine on .Net 7:

```
[07:18:07 PM +00] TotalAllocatedMb=1.47, TotalPauseMs=0.00
[07:18:18 PM +00] TotalAllocatedMb=5271.27, TotalPauseMs=77.91
```

It allocated 5GB of data in 100K iterations. Using `SupportedMethodsList` significantly drops the duration and heap allocations:

```
[07:21:03 PM +00] TotalAllocatedMb=1.47, TotalPauseMs=0.00
[07:21:03 PM +00] TotalAllocatedMb=1.65, TotalPauseMs=0.00
```

EF Core version: 7.1.3
Database provider: (e.g. Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer)
Target framework: (e.g. .NET 7.0.3)
Operating system: Debian (mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/runtime:7.0.3)
